The teachings of the present invention can be readily understood by considering the following detailed description in conjunction with the accompanying drawings, in which:


FIG. 1 illustrates a block diagram of a digital studio system employing the present invention;


FIG. 2 illustrates a splicing operation that is premised on maintaining video presentation continuity;


FIG. 3 illustrates a splicing operation that is premised on maintaining video presentation continuity, where an overlap condition does not exist;


FIG. 4 illustrates an alternative embodiment of the present invention where the splicing operation is premised on maintaining audio presentation continuity; and


FIG. 5 illustrates a flowchart of a method for preserving audio/video lip sync when splicing a plurality of data streams into an output stream.

Returning to FIG. 2, in order to avoid the overlapping of audio access units 2144 and 2241 in the output transport stream 230, the audio access units 2144 is deleted from the output transport stream 230 during the splicing operation.


The detection of the pending overlapping condition is performed by the lip sync evaluator 130.


The method of detection can be summarized as follows:


if A1+B <= A2 +- X, then no overlap condition  (1)


if A1+B>A2 +- X, then overlap condition exists  (2)
